article.description: Eddie Jones' baseline jumper as time expired gave the Miami Heat a 93-91 victory Tuesday night over the Detroit Pistons.
article.headline: Pistons not able to win this time in final seconds

images.name: Jones_Eddie 020305 inline
images.caption: Heat guard Eddie Jones gets off the game-winning shot as time expires.

article.linkText: Heat surge: Jones beats buzzer, Pistons
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Miami Heat think they took another step forward Tuesday night. The Heat blew a 14-point lead to the red-hot Detroit Pistons, but recovered and won the game on Eddie Jones' baseline jumper as time expired. "It just came down to making the big plays," said Alonzo Mourning. "At the beginning of the season, we would have lost this game, but tonight, we perservered and made the right plays." Rod Strickland tied the game by hitting a wide-open 17-footer with 8 seconds left. Jerry Stackhouse had beaten Charlotte on Sunday in the final seconds, but this time lost the ball out of bounds with 2.8 seconds to go. "I was looking for Jon (Barry) in the corner for a 3, but Jim Jackson knocked the ball away from me," Stackhouse said. "I got it back, but then I knew I was running out of time, so I tried to hurry and I just lost the ball." Miami coach Pat Riley knew Stackhouse's turnover was the opening his team needed. "That's a real break when Stack fumbles the ball out of bounds," he said. "That gave us a chance to win it, and that's all we wanted." Jones took Strickland's inbounds pass, went to the baseline and got the shot off over Damon Jones and Michael Curry just as the buzzer sounded. "Three seconds in this game is a lifetime," Jones said. "I knew I could get a fake and a dribble, and the shot just went down." Curry said they were waiting for Jones to get the ball, but it didn't matter. "We knew it would be Eddie or Zo, and they got the ball to Eddie on a flare pass," he said. "I jumped at him to try to get in his field of vision, but give him credit, he made a great shot." With the game tied at 89 and 42.7 seconds left, Jackson fouled Corliss Williamson, who made both free throws to give the Pistons a 91-89 lead. Jackson missed at the other end, but the rebound went out of bounds off the Pistons, setting the stage for Strickland's tying basket. "It was a crazy game, but it was a good finish," Strickland said. "I was struggling tonight, but I just wanted to hold my head up and hit that shot." Jones led the Heat with 24 points, while Mourning had 18 points and 14 rebounds and Brian Grant added 16 points and 15 boards. Stackhouse led the Pistons with 22 points and Chucky Atkins added 17. Detroit lost for just the second time in 10 games. "We've been able to bounce back after losses like this, and we need to do it again," said Cliff Robinson. "These were two teams fighting for a win, and unfortunately, they pulled it out." Detroit trailed by as many as nine in the first half, but went ahead 55-49 on Jon Barry's 3-pointer at the halftime buzzer. Miami, though, scored the first 13 points of the second half, holding the Pistons scoreless for nearly five minutes and taking a 62-55 lead. Detroit cut the margin to 64-62, but Miami responded with a 16-4 run to take an 80-66 lead. "When you let a team score 31 points in a quarter, it just shows that you aren't quite there defensively," Pistons coach Rick Carlisle said. "I thought we played hard most of the night, but we didn't match their intensity in the third quarter and that cost us any chance to take control of the game." The Pistons did narrow the gap to 80-71 by quarter's end, then kept the momentum to pull within four points early in the fourth. Miami pulled away, but Detroit got a break when the Heat were called for a double foul for Anthony Carter and Grant slamming Stackhouse to the floor. Stackhouse made all three free throws, bringing Detroit to 84-79. Barry helped the Heat by being called for a technical foul moments later, but redeemed himself by hitting a 3-pointer at the other end. After a Miami turnover, Jones tied the game at 85 with another 3.

Game notes
The Pistons didn't try their first free throw until the final three minutes of the first half. The Heat had already tried 12 by that point. ... Cliff Robinson scored his 16,000th career point on a third-quarter jumper. ... Pistons center Zeljko Rebraca needed four stitches over his right eye after running into an elbow from Alonzo Mourning in the second quarter. He did not return. ... Miami has gone 20-9 since a Dec. 30 loss to the Pistons at the Palace.
